Aloe Vera

Aloe barbadensis Mill.

Author: Burman
Published: 4/6/1768
Read Time: 6 min
Category:
Location: Pune, Maharashtra, India

Description

Aloe Vera is a plant with thick, resinous leaves that grows in dry areas. Its gel is cool, viscous and transparent, which provides quick relief when applied to the skin. In Ayurveda, it is called "Ghritkumari" or "Kumari" and it calms Pitta Dosha. It is very beneficial in burning sensation, minor wounds, sunburn, acne, hair fall, constipation, sugar control, and boosting immunity. When taken internally, it cleanses the stomach, strengthens the liver, and purifies the blood. When applied externally, it makes the skin glow, reduces wrinkles, and prevents infections.

Medicinal Properties

Anti-inflammatory Antibacterial Antiviral Antifungal Antioxidant Wound healing Laxative Immunomodulator Moisturizing Analgesic (pain-relieving) Hypoglycemic (blood sugar lowering) Anti-ulcer Burn healing

Common Uses

  • Fresh gel applied on sunburn.
  • Gel applied on minor cuts and abrasions.
  • Gel applied on small burns to reduce pain and speed healing.
  • Gel used as natural moisturizer for dry skin.
  • Processed Aloe vera gel or creams for acne, eczema support (topical).
